  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA5-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaivaṉ celavuk kuṟippaṟintu vēṟupaṭṭa talaivikkut (ET: talaimakaṭku) tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said to HER who had changed after understanding HIS intention of going.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA5">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nilanī rārak kuṉṟaṅ kuḻaippa</l>
<l>            vakalvāyp paiñcuṉaip payirkāl yāppak</l>
<l>            kuṟavar koṉṟa kuṟaikkoṭi naṟaippavar</l>
<l>            naṟuṅkā ḻārañ cuṟṟuvaṉa vakaippap</l>
<l>            perumpuyal poḻinta toḻila veḻili </l>
<l>            teṟkēr piraṅku maṟcirak kālaiyu</l>
<l>            maritē kātalarp pirita liṉṟucela</l>
<l>            vikupeyal tarūum vāṭaiyoṭu</l>
<l>            mayaṅkitaḻ maḻaikkaṇ payanta tūtē.</l>

        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
        <l>In the time of the cold season too,</l>
        <l rend="indent4">when the busy clouds,</l>
        <l rend="indent">from which great rain has flown, rise to the South [and] sound,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">for the earth to fill up with water, for the hills to be sprouting,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">for the crops to take root by wide-mouthed fresh mountain pools,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">for fragrant creepers to shoot forth, surrounding the sandal tree</l>
        <l rend="indent2">with fragrant core, deficient creepers weeded by the hill people,<note place="foot">Is <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟavar koṉṟa kuṟai koṭi</term> to be read as an apposition to <term xml:lang="ta">naṟi pavar</term>? What is the message?</note></l>
        <l>separating from the lover [and] going<note place="foot">Here <term xml:lang="ta">pirital</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">celavu</term> are read as a coordinate double subject, but an apposition is equally possible: "going today [which means] separating".</note> today is difficult:</l>
        <l>rain eyes with dishevelled petal [lids] have brought forth the message,</l>
        <l rend="indent3">along with the north wind, which brings showering rain.</l>
        <lg type="alternate" sameAs="7-9b"> 
          <l>difficult [to pass on is] it – the message</l>
	        <l>that [her] rain eyes with dishevelled petals have turned pale,</l>
	        <l>along with the north wind, which brings showering rain,</l>
	        <l>[because of] the lover’s separating [and] going today.<note place="foot">The seemingly simple construction of this poem is not so simple after all. Solution a takes <term xml:lang="ta">kātalar pirital iṉṟu celavu</term> as subjects to <term xml:lang="ta">aritē</term>, which would mean there is an open-ended postposition without apparent function in the following sentence. The predicate of this second sentence would be insufficiently marked as such: <term xml:lang="ta">payanta</term> is by form and usage a peyareccam, and only the lack of a proper predicate for <term xml:lang="ta">tūtu</term> gives rise to the thought that it might be a p.a. n.pl. Solution b is more satisfactory from the syntactic point of view, but still we have to take <term xml:lang="ta">pirital</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">celavu</term> as unmarked datives. They can only be integrated as the reason for the eyes’ turning pale.</note></l>
        </lg>

        </lg>
        
      </div>
